	<article class="post-130608 post type-post status-publish hentry category-disunion tag-seven-days tag-the-civil-war tag-the-iraq-war tag-virginia per-lee-robert-e per-mcclellan-george-b des-civil-war-us-1861-65 des-defense-and-military-forces des-iraq-war-2003-11 geo-virginia" id="post-130608">
	<header class="postHeader">
				<div class="postKicker">
			<span class="kicker"><a href="//opinionator.blogs.nytimes.com/category/disunion/?module=BlogCategory&version=Blog Post&action=Click&contentCollection=Opinion&pgtype=Blogs&region=Header">Disunion</a></span>
		</div>
				<h1 itemprop="headline" class="entry-title">Brothers in Arms</h1>
		<div class="story-meta-footer">
			<address class="byline author vcard" itemprop="author creator" itemtype="//schema.org/Person">
				By Terry L. Jones			</address>
			<!-- date published --><time class="dateline " datetime="2012-07-02T16:27:21+00:00" itemprop="datePublished">July 2, 2012 12:27 pm</time>
			<!-- date updated --><span class="visually-hidden updated">July 2, 2012 12:27 pm</span><button class="button comments-button  theme-kicker" data-skip-to-para-id="">
</button>
		</div>
			</header>
		<div class="entry-content"><p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><webonly><div class="inlineModule"><div class="entry"><div class="thumb"><img alt="Disunion" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/blogs_v3/opinionator/disunion/disunion45.gif" width="50" height="50"></div><p class="summary"> <a href="//opinionator.blogs.nytimes.com/category/disunion/">Disunion</a> follows the Civil War as it unfolded.</p></div></div></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"></webonly>The end of June 1862 found the Union general George B. McClellanâs Army of the Potomac at the end of a week-long retreat during the Seven Days battles, having finally taken up a strong position on Malvern Hill near the James River. Several lines of infantry were arranged along the hillâs slope, with numerous batteries of artillery positioned behind them with a clear view of any approaching Rebels. McClellanâs position seemed nearly impregnable, but Gen. Robert E. Lee believed one more attack on July 1 would destroy the exhausted Union Army. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Col. Eugene Waggamanâs 10th Louisiana was one regiment that participated in the dramatic charge. Waggaman was a deeply religious and popular officer who commanded a motley crew of soldiers. Most of his men were from New Orleans, and they reflected that cityâs cosmopolitan makeup: one company had recruits from 15 foreign countries and another was made up almost entirely of Greeks and Italians. Because many of Waggamanâs men could not speak English, the regiment used French drill commands exclusively. It was motley in other ways as well: the men of the 10th Louisiana were constant camp discipline problems and helped create the notorious reputation of the famed and feared Louisiana Tigers. It would also see its share of hard service: of the regimentâs 845 members, 205 would not survive the Civil War.<span id="more-130608"></span> </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Waggaman was disappointed to learn that his men were to remain in the woods at the base of Malvern Hill as a reserve force during the attack, the same orders they had received in every previous battle of the Seven Days. The Tigers were grumbling about the orders when a courier galloped up to Waggaman and handed him a note. The colonel scanned it and then roared, âFall in!â The 10th Louisiana would fight after all.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Waggaman led the regiment forward and halted at a fence that skirted a large field. The Yankee line was clearly visible 500 yards in the distance, but the only protective cover was a shallow ravine about halfway to the enemy. Waggaman decided to cover the open ground as quickly as possible and then regroup in the safety of the gully before the final charge. The regiment suffered a number of casualties from artillery fire during the sprint across the field but finally made it to the ravine. Waggaman gave the order to fix bayonets and then took up a position in the center of the regiment. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">âMen,â he yelled, âwe are ordered to charge the cannon in our front and take them. The Tenth Regiment has been in reserve all week, and every other Louisiana regiment has been in action. Not a shot must be fired until we get to the guns. Now, men, we are going to charge. Remember Butler and the women of New Orleans. Forward, charge!â</p>
<div class="w427"><img src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2012/07/02/opinion/02disunion/02disunion-blog427.jpg" alt="DESCRIPTION" /><span class="credit">Library of Congress</span> <span class="caption">A Union charge at the Battle of Malvern Hill.</span></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Thirty-six Union cannons swept the field with a deadly barrage of iron as the Tigers sprang from the gully. Those men who survived the murderous fire and still had heart for the fight closed in on the Union position held by Gen. Thomas Meagherâs Irish Brigade. Meagher, an Irish native who had participated in the unsuccessful 1849 uprising against Britain before migrating to the United States, formed the brigade a year earlier by recruiting mostly Irish immigrants. It was a battle-hardened crew; over the course of the war the Irish Brigade suffered the third-highest casualty rate of any brigade in the Army of the Potomac. Despite their rapid replacement rate, the soldiers in the brigade never forgot their native land and conspicuously carried green Irish flags on the battlefield. For its pomp as much as its valor, the brigade became one of the most famous units of the war. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Watching from the base of Malvern Hill, one Confederate soldier remembered how the Tigers disappeared into a cloud of smoke and flame as if they had been swallowed by hell itself. But Waggaman and a handful of his men managed to make their way to the enemyâs line and engage the Irish Brigade in a bloody hand-to-hand fight. One of Waggamanâs men was bayoneted through the neck while standing next to him.</p>
<div class="w190 right"><img src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2012/07/02/opinion/disunion-jemison/disunion-jemison-articleInline.jpg" id="100000001641377" width="190" height="223" alt="Pvt. Edwin Francis Jemison of the 2nd Louisiana Regiment, killed at the Battle of Malvern Hill." /><span class="credit">Library of Congress</span><span class="caption">Pvt. Edwin Francis Jemison of the 2nd Louisiana Regiment, killed at the Battle of Malvern Hill.</span></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Waggaman carried his familyâs 150-year-old sword and used it to slash at the enemy that now had him surrounded. He knocked aside a Yankeeâs musket, pointed square at his face at point-blank range, before the man could fire it. Cries of âBayonet him!â and âKill him!â rose all around as Waggaman continued hacking his way through the Irishmen. Within minutes, however, the colonel and 16 of his men were overpowered and captured (but not before Waggaman threw away his sword to try to keep it from falling into enemy hands). </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The 10th Louisiana was the only regiment in its brigade that penetrated the federal position atop Malvern Hill, but the Tigers paid dearly for the honor: of the 318 men engaged in the fight, 18 were killed, 35 wounded and 18 reported missing. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">While the Irish Brigade was licking its wounds some of the men requested new muskets to replace the ones destroyed during the melee with the Tigers. Gen. Edwin Sumner, the brigadeâs corps commander, at first refused to issue the weapons because he thought the soldiers had simply thrown them away during the weeklong retreat from Richmond. He changed his mind, however, when he was shown what was described as a âpile of muskets with cracked and splintered stocks, bent barrels and twisted bayonetsâ â evidence of the fierce clash with the Louisianians. One soldier told the general, âThe boys got in a scrimmage with the Tigers, and when the bloody villains took to their knives, the boys mostly forgot their bayonets, and went to work in the style they were used to, and licked them well, sir.â</p>
<div class="w151 right module">
<div class="entry">
<h6 class="kicker">Related</h6>
<h5><a href="//www.nytimes.com/interactive/2010/10/29/opinion/20101029-civil-war.html">Disunion Highlights</a></h5>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><img class="w75" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2010/11/08/opinion/civil-war-sumter75/civil-war-sumter75-popup.jpg" alt="Fort Sumter" /></p>
<p class="summary">Explore multimedia from the series and navigate through past posts, as well as photos and articles from the Times archive.</p>
<ul class="refer">
<li><a href="//www.nytimes.com/interactive/2010/10/29/opinion/20101029-civil-war.html">See the Highlights Â»</a></li>
</ul>
</div>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Colonel Waggaman and the other Tigers captured on Malvern Hill were released several weeks later as part of a prisoner exchange. Amazingly, the colonel was reunited with his sword: a Union soldier had picked it up on the battlefield, and Gen. Winfield Scott Hancock ordered it returned to the Rebel colonel. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Waggaman eventually rose to command the Confederate Armyâs Louisiana Brigade and returned home after the surrender. When the war ended, the Irish Brigade regiments were disbanded, save for the 69th New York. It was designated a National Guard unit and gained more fame as âThe Fighting 69thâ while serving in both world wars. In Louisiana, National Guard units were also formed in the postwar period, and they traced their ancestry back to the Louisiana Tigers. </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">As it turned out, the New Yorkers and Louisianians were destined to meet on the battlefield one more time. In 2004, Louisianaâs 256th Infantry Brigade was federalized for the war in Iraq but it needed additional manpower to bring it up to full strength. As a result, the 69th New York was ordered to join the 256th at Fort Hood, Tex. Reflecting on the turn of events, the 256thâs Lt. Col. Mark Kerry declared: âWeâve met before. And we have quite a history between us, and now weâre going to war with them. I couldnât be happier. I guess we can file this away under the heading âThe Civil War Is Really Over.ââ</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">On Jan. 2, 2005, one of the 256th Brigadeâs Humvees was destroyed by an I.E.D. in Iraq, killing six members of the modern Louisiana Tiger Brigade and one man from the 69th New York. The seven soldiers were the descendants of bitter enemies that fought one another in a vicious civil war nearly 150 years earlier.  In the end, they died as brothers in arms.  </p>
<hr/>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>Follow Disunion at <a href="https://www.twitter.com/NYTcivilwar/">twitter.com/NYTcivilwar</a> or join us <a href="//www.facebook.com/pages/Civil-War-The-New-York-Times/171184126228555">on Facebook</a>.</em></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>Sources: Michael Cavanagh, âMemoirs of Gen. Thomas Francis Meagherâ; Terry L. Jones, âLeeâs Tigers: The Louisiana Infantry in the Army of Northern Virginiaâ; Terry L. Jones, âThe Louisiana Journeyâ; Official Records, Vol. XI, Pt. II; New Orleans Times Picayune, May 16, 1862; Eugene Waggaman to Louis Janin, July 1862, Janin Family Papers, Huntington Library; Army Times, July 6, 2004.</em></p>
<hr/>
<div class="w75 left"><img src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2011/07/27/opinion/disunion-terry-jones/disunion-terry-jones-thumbStandard.jpg" alt=" Terry L. Jones" /></div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><em>Terry L. Jones is a professor of history at the University of Louisiana, Monroe and the author of six books on the Civil War.</em></p>
